Your Assignment Tasks
Your work is contained entirely in the file exploration.py. The file has clearly marked TODO sections for
each part. The framework calls your functions automatically—you only need to fill in the logic.
1. Frontier Detection and Clustering (12 points)
Replace the random frontier detector with a proper implementation. A frontier cell is a free cell that has
at least one unknown 4-neighbor (up, down, left, right). Your implementation should:
• Scan the occupancy grid and identify all frontier cells.
• Cluster frontier cells into contiguous frontier regions using BFS (flood-fill) with 4-connectivity. Each
cluster represents a connected segment of the exploration boundary.
• Filter out regions with fewer than FRONTIER_MIN_SIZE cells (defined in config.py, default 3).
These tiny clusters are noise and should be discarded.
• Return a list of FrontierRegion objects, each containing the cluster cells, centroid, and size.
Use the function template detect_frontiers() in exploration.py. Guidance comments and a
scaffolded structure are provided in the file.
2. Goal Selection Strategies (16 points total)
Implement two goal selection strategies to replace the random baseline.
Part 2a: Nearest Frontier (10 points) — Select the closest reachable frontier cell by path cost. For
each frontier region whose centroid is not blacklisted, plan a path from the robot’s current position to
the centroid and choose the goal with the minimum path cost. If a centroid falls on a non-free cell
(e.g., a wall), snap it to the nearest free cell. Use the function template select_goal_nearest()
in exploration.py.
Hint: Convert the robot’s world-coordinate position (state.robot_x, state.robot_y) to grid coor-
dinates using CELL_SIZE. Remember that row corresponds to y and column corresponds to x.
Part 2b: Custom Strategy (6 points) — Design and implement your own goal selection strategy that
outperforms the nearest-frontier strategy on at least one of the provided maps. Your strategy should
consider factors beyond pure distance. Some ideas to explore:
• Cost-utility: maximize frontier_size/path_cost, preferring large, close frontiers over small, distant ones.
• Information gain: estimate how much unknown area surrounds each frontier.
• Dead-end avoidance: penalize frontiers deep in narrow corridors.
Use the function template select_goal_custom() in exploration.py. Briefly describe your ap-
proach in a code comment.
3. Robust Exploration Loop (12 points)
Implement the main decision-making callback that the framework calls once per iteration. The random
baseline ignores many edge cases that arise during real exploration. Your implementation must handle:
• Path validation: As the robot discovers new obstacles, a previously planned path may become blocked.
Validate the remaining path each iteration using validate_path() and clear it if invalid to trigger
replanning.
• Goal selection and planning: When no valid path exists, call the goal selector to pick a frontier, then
plan a path to it using plan_path().
• Blacklisting unreachable goals: If plan_path() returns None for a goal (no feasible path exists),
add the goal to state.blacklisted_goals and try another frontier.
