• Completion detection: When no reachable frontiers remain, set state.exploration_complete
= True to signal the framework to stop.
Use the function template exploration_step() in exploration.py. When you find a valid path,
set state.current_path and state.current_path_index = 1 (skip the start cell, which is the
robot’s current position). The framework then executes the path automatically.
Optional Bonus: A* Path Planning
The provided path planner in planner.py uses Dijkstra’s algorithm, which is correct but explores cells uni-
formly in all directions. For distant goals, Dijkstra wastes significant wall-clock time expanding unnecessary
cells. You can upgrade the planner to A* by adding an admissible heuristic (e.g., Euclidean distance to goal)
to the priority queue—the only change is replacing priority= g(n) with priority= g(n) + h(n). This does
not change path quality (A* finds the same optimal path as Dijkstra), but makes planning dramatically faster.
This upgrade is optional and not separately graded, but it is strongly recommended, as a slow planner eats
into your time budget. Use the function template plan_path() in exploration.py.
Report Requirements
In addition to your code, submit a short PDF report (report.pdf) worth 10 points. The report should
contain:
1. Coverage plots (5 points) — For each of the three provided maps, plot coverage (%) versus time or step
count, comparing the random baseline, nearest-frontier, and your custom strategy. You can collect data
by running your implementation with different --strategy flags and recording the coverage history.
2. Discussion (5 points) — Briefly discuss your findings. Why do certain strategies perform better on cer-
tain maps? Where does the greedy nearest-frontier approach struggle? What does your custom strategy
capture that nearest-frontier misses? Keep the discussion concise, a few paragraphs is sufficient.
Getting Started
Run the exploration with the random baseline to see the framework in action:
python run_exploration.py --map open_room --strategy random
Once you implement your strategies, test them with:
python run_exploration.py --map office --strategy nearest
Available options:
• Maps: open_room, office, cave
• Strategies: random (baseline), nearest (your Part 2a), custom (your Part 2b)
• Visualization speed: --speed 0.01 (fast) or --speed 0.1 (slow)
• No visualization: --no-vis (useful for collecting timing data)
• Reproducibility: --seed 42 (fix the random seed)
A validation script is included. Run python validate_submission.py to check that your exploration.py
file imports correctly, has all required functions, and passes basic sanity checks. The code scripts are self-
explanatory, so we encourage you to read through them to understand exactly what is being checked.
